questionTemplates.text:
W: Do you think it will rain tonight?
M: Not a chance.
{a}

W: Did you go to Yellowstone Park for vacation last year?
M: I couldn't make it last December. But I finally went there three months later. I plan to visit again next year.
{a}

W: These tomatoes are huge! You must have watered them a lot.
M: Yes, I did. They ought to be ripe enough to pick by next Friday when we have our picnic.
{a}

M: You are looking a little overwhelmed.
W: Exactly. You know I got a million things to do and all of them have to be finished within three hours.
{a}

M: Are you really leaving for Hawaii,Mary?
W: I think so, I've got my ticket and I'm anxious to see Tom there.
{a}

W: Could you tell me what I should do if my car breaks down?
M: Well, I'm sure you won't have any trouble, Mrs. Smith, but if something should happen, just call this number. They'll see that you get help.
{a}

W: My printer is out of paper. I will run and get some.
M: I will go with you. I need some fresh air.
{a}

W: Bob, are you ready? What on earth are you doing? Don't you know the curtain goes up at exactly seven?
M: My shirt's caught in the zipper. Could you give me a hand?
{a}

W: I want to tell you my problem, Mike.
M: OK! Let's discuss it together.
{a}

W: Look! They are lining up at Gate 10.
M: Hurry up. It's time to check in for our train.
{a}

F: This book is very interesting.
M: It is, isn't it?
{a}

W: I received an email yesterday from Henry. Do you remember? He was one of the chairpersons of our students union.
M: Yes, but I haven't heard from him for ages. Actually I've been out of touch with him since our first reunion after graduation.
{a}

M: What is your address?
W: No. 145, Shanghai Road.
{a}

W: Lucy told me she would meet you at the gate of the station.
M: This time I will not make a mistake again.
{a}

W: What can I do for you?
M: May I see some of your best T-shirts?
{a}

M: Sorry to have kept you waiting, Madam. I've located your luggage. It was left behind in Paris and won't arrive until later this evening.
W: Oh, I can't believe this. Have it delivered to my hotel then, I guess.
{a}

M: What did you think of the mid-term exam?
W: I was expecting it to be easy, but at the end of the first hour, I was still on the first page. I hardly had time to get to the last question.
{a}

M: How about your history lecture yesterday?
W: We had expected Professor Adams to come. But Mrs. Baker was also a good lecturer and she did a quite good job.
{a}

W: You see I still have this pain in my back, this medicine the doctor gave me was supposed to make me feel better by now.
M: Maybe you should've taken it three times a day as you were told.
{a}

W: Have you found anything wrong with my stomach?
M: Not yet. I'm still examining. I'll let you know the result next week.
{a}

W: This plane should have taken off half an hour ago.
M: I'm sorry for the delay. We'll be taking off shortly.
{a}

M: Where are you at the moment?
W: We're visiting Beijing.
{a}

M: My radio doesn't work. What do you think I should do?
W: Why not call Mr. White?
{a}

W: What sport do you like, Mike?
M: I prefer playing basketball to playing football.
{a}
